WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:14.149
Kevin Connolly: This is one we have some data on. So, like, the application start to getting a job offer in the industry, we call it time to hire. There's a few other timing metrics, but this time to hire one is mostly a reflection of recruiting team process.

2
00:00:14.150 --> 00:00:19.599
Kevin Connolly: The median for engineering roles across our company base, which is pre-representative, is about 40 days.

3
00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:36.949
Kevin Connolly: This will vary for, university hiring or internships where larger companies sometimes do just, like, hiring career fair sprints. But you'll know from context whether their process is, like, we're gonna try and hire people, like, literally today at this, like, on-site event, or…

4
00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:50.619
Kevin Connolly: A good recruiting team will tell you the typical process, and there's a typical process in, like, structured tech interviewing, something like recruiter screen, screen, assessment, or take home. Sometimes they flip the order of them, then you do, like, an on-site panel to offer maybe a background check.

5
00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:54.580
Kevin Connolly: So, 50 days on average.

6
00:00:54.750 --> 00:01:10.089
Kevin Connolly: 40 days by median, and then, of course, distribution is a distribution, so some teams will go really fast. Typically, if they're smaller, it's the smallest teams that tend to go the fastest, and you get up to larger enterprise orgs. They don't have the outliers, like, they're not super slow, but they're also not super fast.

7
00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:13.190
Kevin Connolly: And I have a chart here. This is,

8
00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:25.939
Kevin Connolly: business versus tech roles, again, split out, so you can see, like, an average time to hire, that's the applications start to getting higher, like, offers signed, it's, like, 45 days, and it's pretty… I think the notable thing here is that it's stable. So, like, this particular metric is…

9
00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:30.099
Kevin Connolly: Probably more a reflection of just when people get

10
00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:40.019
Kevin Connolly: scheduled for an onsite, they want to wait a week or two, or there's, like, scheduling delays between interview steps, so, like, the weeks kind of accumulate and they all shake out to being…

11
00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:43.339
Kevin Connolly: Anywhere between 3 to 5 weeks, 6 weeks.

12
00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:52.300
Kevin Connolly: And then this, I pulled… this is the, hire… the candidate experience, so you can say, like.

13
00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:58.749
Kevin Connolly: sometimes there's a small startup will have, like, an interview process. It's like, you talk to a hiring manager, then you talk to

14
00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:11.340
Kevin Connolly: the CEO, and then you get hired. So, like, your grand total is, like, an hour and a half of interviews. Other more structured companies, and that's what this is, like, it's the aggregate hours of interviews for the candidate that gets hired.

15
00:02:11.510 --> 00:02:28.420
Kevin Connolly: Split out by business and tech roles. But you can see, like, you can kind of expect to do, like, three and a half, maybe four hours of interviewing if you're gonna apply to a company, but some companies, depending on the role, process, details, you could be an outlier, get out to the tails, like, seven hours of interviewing aggregated over that.

16
00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:31.759
Kevin Connolly: 4 weeks of process.

